response:
Denote by $O$ the center of the semicircle, by $A$ one of the intersection points between the semicircle and the circle, and by $B$ the point of tangency of both circles, as in the picture below.
[asy]
unitsize(6mm);
defaultpen(linewidth(.8pt)+fontsize(8pt));
dotfactor=4;

filldraw(Circle((0,0),4),grey,black);
filldraw(Circle((0,2),2),white,black);
draw((-4,0)--(4,0),black+linewidth(.75));
draw(Circle((0,2),2),black+linewidth(.75));
dot((0,2));
draw((0,2)--(2,2+2*dir(60)),black+linewidth(.75));
label("$O$",O,N);
label("$A$",A,NE);
label("$B$",B,N);
[/asy]
By the Pythagorean Theorem on $\triangle{OAB}$, it follows that $|OB|=4$. Thus the area of the semicircle exceeds the area of the second circle by $4\pi$, so the shaded area is $\boxed{\frac{4\pi}{{\pi\cdot4^2}}=\boxed{\frac{1}{4}}}$</think>

